Cite web<!--\n-->|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/myydyimmat/kaikki/kotimaiset/albumit<!--\n-->|title=Kaikkien aikojen myydyimm\u00e4t kotimaiset albumit<!--\n-->|publisher=Musiikkituottajat \u2013 IFPI Finland<!--\n-->|language=Finnish<!--\n-->|accessdate=27 August 2013<!--\n-->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"FIN best for\">{{Cite web<!--\n-->|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/myydyimmat/kaikki/ulkomaiset/albumit<!--\n-->|title=Kaikkien aikojen myydyimm\u00e4t ulkomaiset albumit<!--\n-->|publisher=Musiikkituottajat \u2013 IFPI Finland<!--\n-->|language=Finnish<!--\n-->|accessdate=27 August 2013<!--\n-->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"FIN all sales 2007\">The first list is the list of best-selling domestic albums of 2007 in Finland and the second is that of the best-selling foreign albums:\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/myydyimmat/2007/kotimaiset/albumit|title=Myydyimm\u00e4t kotimaiset albumit vuonna 2007|language=Finnish|publisher=Musiikkituottajat&nbsp;\u2013 IFPI Finland|accessdate=27 August 2013}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/myydyimmat/2007/ulkomaiset/albumit|title=Myydyimm\u00e4t ulkomaiset albumit vuonna 2007|language=Finnish|publisher=Musiikkituottajat&nbsp;\u2013 IFPI Finland|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nightwish.com Nightwish's Official Website]\n\n{{Nightwish}}\n\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Nightwish albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Abbey Road Studios]]\n[[Category:Spinefarm Records albums]]\n[[Category:Nuclear Blast albums]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Dark Passion Play\n| type       = Studio Album\n| artist     = [[Nightwish]]\n| cover      = Dark Passion Play.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 26 September 2007\n| recorded   = Petrax Studios, [[Hollola]], E-Major Studios, [[Kerava]] and [[Finnvox Studios]], Helsinki, Finland<br>[[Abbey Road Studios]], London, England<br>September 2006 \u2013 March 2007\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Symphonic metal]]<ref name=\"all\" />\n| length     = 75:45\n| label      = [[Spinefarm Records|Spinefarm]] <small>(Finland)</small><br>[[Nuclear Blast]] <small>(Europe)</small><br>[[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]] <small>(North America)</small>\n| producer   = [[Tuomas Holopainen]], Co-Produced by Tero Kinnunen & Mikko Karmila\n| prev_title = [[Once (Nightwish album)|Once]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[Imaginaerum]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Dark Passion Play\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Eva (Nightwish song)|Eva]]\n | single1date = 25 May 2007 <small>(Digital release)</small>\n | single2     = [[Amaranth (song)|Amaranth]]\n | single2date = 22 August 2007\n | single3     = [[Er\u00e4maan Viimeinen|Er\u00e4maan Viimeinen/Last of the Wilds]]\n | single3date = 5 December 2007 <small>([[Finland]])</small>\n | single4     = [[Bye Bye Beautiful]]\n | single4date = 15 February 2008\n | single5     = [[The Islander (song)|The Islander]]\n | single5date = 21 May 2008\n}}\n}}\n'''''Dark Passion Play''''' is the sixth studio album by [[Finns|Finnish]] [[symphonic metal]] band [[Nightwish]], released on 26 September 2007 in Finland, 28 September in Europe and 2 October 2007 in the [[The United States of America|United States]]. It is the first album without original vocalist [[Tarja Turunen]], who was dismissed in 2005, as well as the first album involving future member [[Troy Donockley]] on [[uilleann pipes]] and [[tin whistle]]. It is the first of only two albums with vocalist [[Anette Olzon]], who was eventually dismissed in 2012 after the release of the band's subsequent album, ''[[Imaginaerum]]''.<ref>http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/anette-olzon-i-didnt-leave-nightwish-i-was-fired/ Lead songwriter</ref> [[Tuomas Holopainen]] has referred to it as the \"album that saved his life\".<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/group/Tuomas+Holopainen/forum/29012/_/321352|title=TUOMAS HOLOPAINEN \u2013 \"Dark Passion Play Is The Album That Saved My Life\"  \u2013 Tuomas Holopainen Discussions \u2013 Last.fm}}</ref>\n\nThe first single, \"[[Eva (Nightwish song)|Eva]]\", was leaked on the Internet six days before its official release, prompting the band to release the single earlier to boost downloads. Several other versions of the song were posted on YouTube and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|torrent]] sites a month later; the entire album with record label [[voice-over]]s had been leaked on the Internet by 2 August. The full album (without voiceovers) was leaked on 21 September 2007, as a result of several stores in [[Mexico]] selling the retail album much prior to the worldwide release date.\n\nPre-orders for ''Dark Passion Play'' had it certified gold in Finland before it had even been released.<ref name=\"kerrang_2008\"/> The album debuted at number one in 6 European countries, selling over 100,000 copies in [[Finland]] ([[List of music recording certifications#Albums|triple platinum]]). In February 2008, the album was certified quadruple-platinum in Finland, after having sold over 120,000 copies, which makes it one of the 40 best-selling albums of all time in the country.{{r|FIN best dom}}{{r|FIN best for}} Worldwide, ''Dark Passion Play'' has sold almost 2&nbsp;million copies since its release.\n\n==Background and production==\n[[File:Anette Olzon 2009.jpg|thumb|220px|right|[[Anette Olzon]] (pictured), joined [[Nightwish]] replacing [[Tarja Turunen]].]]\nOn 21 October 2005, after the ''[[Once Upon a Tour]]'', the band's lead singer [[Tarja Turunen]] was dismissed via an [[open letter]]. In search of a replacement, the band conducted auditions from 17 March 2006 to 15 January 2007, receiving over 2000 demo tapes in the process.<ref name=\"audition\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nightwish.com/en/news/archive?month=01&year=2007|title=The auditions for the new vocalist have ended|date=26 January 2007|accessdate=25 October 2009|work=|publisher=Nightwish's Official Website}}</ref> Amidst much speculation the new singer was officially announced on 24 May 2007 to be [[Anette Olzon]], previously the singer for the Swedish AOR band [[Alyson Avenue]]. In an interview, Holopainen said they had made the decision in January 2007 based on the impression she made while performing the song \"[[Ever Dream]]\" from the album ''[[Century Child]]''.<ref name=\"nw bio\">{{cite web|url= http://www.nightwish.com/en/band/biography|title=The Band \u2013 Biography: The history of Nightwish|publisher=Nightwish's Official Website|accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Of course it's gonna be a huge task for the singer&nbsp;\u2013 she will always be compared to Tarja but I'm pretty confident that she'll do well.<br/><small>-[[Tuomas Holopainen]] regarding [[Anette Olzon]]'s ability<ref name=\"nw bio\" /></small>}}\n\nThe recording process started in the spring 2006 in different studios across Europe; the drums were recorded by Nevalainen in [[Hollola]], Finland, at the Petrax Studios, [[Emppu Vuorinen]] recorded the guitars in [[Kerava]], Finland, were also record the keyboards by Holopainen and the bass parts by [[Marco Hietala]].<ref name=\"studio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Nightwish+release+Finlands+costliest-ever+album+/1135230577662|title=Nightwish release Finland's costliest-ever album|date=25 September 2007|accessdate=25 October 2009|newspaper=Helsingin Sanomat}}</ref> Hietala is also the band's male singer, and in 2006 Hietala sung some of the new songs to record the demo versions as a base for the final recordings, with definitive vocals being recorded by Olzon at the Petrax in March 2007, immediately after being chosen to replace Tarja Turunen, and nearly two months before her name was given to the media and the fans.<ref name=\"studio\" />\n\nWhen the drummer [[Jukka Nevalainen]] was asked about the overall cost of the new album, he was quoted as saying \"Roughly half a million... We don't know the exact sum down to the euros and cents as yet.\"<ref name=\"studio\" /> Half of this cost was incurred in London, over an expensive eight days at the [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London, UK, during which time the [[London Session Orchestra]], the [[Metro Voices|Metro Voices Choir]], a gospel choir and two Irish musicians recorded their parts at the studio.<ref name=\"studio\" /> In an interview with ''[[Kerrang!]]'' on 16 August 2008 [[Tuomas Holopainen]] recalled:{{quote|After the split with Tarja, we started writing without a singer, and it was quite a liberating feeling. We knew the right girl was out there somewhere, so we could just concentrate on the music. It took 10 months in the studio to make, but the atmosphere was so good and liberating there was a lot of bittersweet relief in the air. It was an extremely inspirational time.<ref name=\"kerrang_2008\">Ruskell, Nick. ''[[Kerrang!]]'' August 16, 2008, #1223. Treausre Chest. An Ultimate Portrait of a Life in Rock. Tuomas Holopainen. p 54</ref>}}\n\"When I think back to it, it was such a crucial point to so many people, we didn't even realise back then but it showed us what we would be doing for the next year of our lives. We were never nervous about Anette, or the album being good, but we just couldn't tell how people would take it. Would they like Anette? Would they like the music? That was in the back of our minds all the time. And there was such a huge amount of money involved, over 800.000 euros, that we needed to sell at least a few albums to get going,\" Tuomas Holopainen was recalling in 2008.<ref name=\"kerrang_2008\"/> According to [[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]], the album's studio bill was around 680,000 USD.<ref name=\"usd dB\">{{cite web |last1=Chase |first1=Jesse |title=Katatonia \u2013 \"Brave Murder Day\" |url=https://www.decibelmagazine.com/2007/11/18/katatonia-brave-murder-day/ |website=[[Decibel (magazine)|Decibel]] |accessdate=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\nThe orchestral line-up featured 66 members from the London Philharmonic Orchestra, 32 singers from The Metro Voices and twelve gospel singers.<ref name=\"studio\" /> The final mixing process spent more than 75 days at the Finnvox Studios in [[Kitee]], Finland, the same place where Nightwish recorded all their previous albums.<ref name=\"studio\" />\n\n==Music description==\nBefore the album's release, band leader [[Tuomas Holopainen]] said in an interview that the album would have a lot in common with the previous album ''[[Once (Nightwish album)|Once]]''. For example, the band have kept the new kind of heavier songs, such as \"Master Passion Greed\", \"Whoever Brings the Night\", \"7 Days to the Wolves\", and \"[[Bye Bye Beautiful]]\", but additionally there are softer ballads, such as \"Meadows of Heaven\", \"[[Eva (Nightwish song)|Eva]]\", and \"[[The Islander (song)|The Islander]]\". This album includes lots of guest musicians and orchestral parts, just like ''Once'', but with a bigger level.\n\nJust like the album ''Once'', Nightwish included many new influences and experimentations in several tracks. On ''Once'', much inspiration came from Native American music, especially \"Creek Mary's Blood\", which featured Lakota Indian musician John Two-Hawks. However, on ''Dark Passion Play'', much inspiration comes from Finnish and Irish culture and music, which can be clearly heard on \"Last of the Wilds\". Songs like \"Master Passion Greed\" and \"Cadence of Her Last Breath\" included [[thrash metal]] and [[alternative metal]] elements as well, displaying the newer, more modern sound of the band. In a later interview, Hietela said the band \"didn't get as far with it [the song] as we wanted to when we recorded the song in the studio \u2013 we wanted it to be a little bit more impressive\".<ref name=\"teamrock\">{{cite web|title=The 10 Best Nightwish Songs|url=http://teamrock.com/feature/2016-06-13/the-10-best-nightwish-songs-marco-hietala-once-dark-passion-play-imaginaerum-endless-forms-most-beautiful|website=TeamRock|publisher=TeamRock|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=13 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nHolopainen also said that there are darker pieces reminiscent of the album ''[[Century Child]]'', such as \"The Poet and the Pendulum\", and some others. It will be a dark album, both musically and lyrically. Even though the album is much more upbeat than ''Century Child''. Songs that reflect this mood are for example the second single \"[[Amaranth (song)|Amaranth]]\" and \"Bye Bye Beautiful\"'s B-side \"Escapist.\"\n\n{{cquote|The extremes are there more than ever before. So it's not going to be like ''Century Child'' 2. There is more hope in some of the new songs.<br/>-[[Tuomas Holopainen]], band leader, keyboardist, and main composer.}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"about\" />\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"all\" />\n| rev3 = ''[[Blabbermouth.net]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|7.5|10}}<ref name=\"mouth\" />\n| rev4 =''[[Metal Hammer]]'' (GER)\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|6|7}}<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.metal-hammer.de/reviews/nightwish-dark-passion-play-2/|title=Nightwish :: Dark Passion Play |language=German |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=28 September 2007 |accessdate=5 July 2016 }}</ref>\n| rev5 =metal1.info (GER)\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|9.5|10}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metal1.info/metal-reviews/nightwish-dark-passion-play/|title=Nightwish \u2013 \"Dark Passion Play\" |language=German |website=metal1.info |date=6 April 2013 |accessdate=5 July 2016 }}</ref>\n| rev6 = [[Metal Storm (webzine)|Metal Storm]]\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|7.5|10}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalstorm.net/pub/review.php?review_id=4678 |title=Nightwish \u2013 Dark Passion Play review |publisher=[[Metal Storm (webzine)|Metal Storm]] |date=26 September 2007 |accessdate=5 July 2016 }}</ref>\n| rev7 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev7score= 5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/nightwish-dark-passion-play/ |title=Nightwish: Dark Passion Play|publisher=popmatters.com |date= 3 October 2007|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Ultimate Guitar Archive|Ultimate-Guitar.com]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|9|10|score=8.8/10 stars}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/reviews/compact_discs/nightwish/dark_passion_play/index.html |title=Imaginaerum Review |publisher=[[Ultimate Guitar]] |date=12 January 2011 |accessdate=5 July 2016 }}</ref>\n}}\nThe album has sold more than 130,000 copies in Finland to date, placing 26th on the list of best-selling Finnish albums ever released,<ref>[http://www.ifpi.fi/tilastot/myydyimmat/kaikki Statistics by IFPI] Retrieved on 17 March 2009</ref> which has granted it a [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] certification four times. Worldwide, it has sold over 700,000 copies by the end of 2007 and about 2&nbsp;million copies to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thrashhits.com/2011/11/album-nightwish-imaginaerum/|title=Album: Nightwish \u2013 Imaginaerum|publisher=Thrash Hits}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wumpsee.com/event-detail/1465/north-american-imaginaerum-tour-with-nightwish|title=North American Imaginaerum Tour With Nightwish|publisher=Wumpsee.com}}</ref> It has been certified as Platinum in Germany<ref name=\"sales ger\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musikindustrie.de/gold_platin_datenbank/|title=Gold/Platinum: Date bases|accessdate=1 June 2010|work=|publisher=Bundesverband Musikindustrie}}</ref> and Hungary,<ref name=\"sales hun\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mahasz.hu/?menu=slagerlistak&menu2=archivum|title=Archive- Nightwish|accessdate=7 June 2010|publisher=Mahasz.hu}}</ref> and Gold in Austria,<ref name=\"sales aut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.at/?section=goldplatin |title=Gold & Platin |accessdate=1 June 2010 |publisher=\u00d6sterreichischen Musikwirtschaft |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511092844/http://www.ifpi.at/?section=goldplatin |archivedate=11 May 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Poland,<ref name=\"dpp charts\">{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/28445|title=Nightwish - Dark Passion Play|work=|publisher=aCharts.us|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref> Sweden<ref name=\"sales swe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.se/?page_id=67 |title=Gold and Platinum |accessdate=7 June 2010 |publisher=Ifpi.se |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211234149/http://www.ifpi.se/?page_id=67 |archivedate=11 February 2009 }}</ref> and Switzerland;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swisscharts.com/search_certifications.asp?search=Nightwish|title=Awards|publisher=Swisscharts.com}}</ref> Dark Passion Play is also the most successful Nightwish album in UK and USA<ref name=\"uk usa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=89498|title=Behind-the-Scenes Footage From Scandinavian Tour Posted Online|date=29 January 2008|accessdate=1 June 2010|work=Blabbermouth.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090727171545/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=89498|archivedate=27 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> with sales in the United States of over 134,000 copies.<ref>http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=168440{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2008, the album has topped the album charts in six countries; the singles, \"[[Amaranth (song)|Amaranth]]\" and \"[[Er\u00e4maan Viimeinen]]\" have both reached the first position on Finnish charts.<ref name=\"fin charts\">{{cite web|url=http://finnishcharts.com/search.asp?search=Nightwish&cat=a|title=Extended Search: Nightwish|accessdate=1 June 2010|publisher= Hung Medien|work=Allmusic}}</ref> According to [[Last.fm]], \"Dark Passion Play\" is their most played album, and its successful single \"Amaranth\" has as of February 2009 been holding the position of most played song since its release.<ref name=\"fin charts\" />\n\nThe album was also critically acclaimed in most reviews. ''[[Allmusic]]'' called the album a \"sort of opera aria\" and praised \"[[Bye Bye Beautiful]]\", on a track pic and \"[[Eva (Nightwish song)|Eva]]\", that they say it focus on the new vocalist vocal abilities.<ref name=\"all\">{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/r1186341|title=Dark Passion Play- Nightwish|accessdate=1 June 2010|website= [[Allmusic]]}}</ref>\n\nThe album was also given a positive review by ''[[Blabbermouth]]'''s Keith Bergman, who gave the album a 7.5 out of 10 and stated that it \"may not be a masterpiece throughout, but it's got enough moments of symphonic metal bliss to warrant a high recommendation.<ref name=\"mouth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1264|title=Nightwish- Dark Passion Play (Roadrunner)|date=22 December 2007|accessdate=1 June 2010|work=Blabbermouth.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308074221/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=1264|archivedate=8 March 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[About.com]]'' writer, Chad Bowar, gave the album a score of 4 out of 5 stars, calling ''Dark Passion Play'' \"an excellent album that's right up there with the best the band has done.\"<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/nightwishdark.htm|title=Nightwish \u2013 Dark Passion Play|date=22 December 2007|accessdate=1 June 2010|publisher=[[About.com]]|work=}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2016, an article by Teamrock considers Dark Passion Play as one of the \"best albums of this century\", ranking it at number 60 on their countdown of the \"21st century's greatest albums\".<ref>http://teamrock.com/feature/2016-07-18/why-nightwish-s-dark-passion-play-is-one-of-the-best-albums-of-this-century</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the [[NHL]] hockey team [[Minnesota Wild]] featured the album's first track \"The Poet and the Pendulum\" in their season trailer.<ref>https://twitter.com/nightcom_ru/status/535163361714270208</ref>\n\nThe instrumental version of Whoever Brings the Night was featured in a 2011 [[puzzle-platformer]] [[video game]], [[LittleBigPlanet 2]].<ref>[[LittleBigPlanet 2#Music]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Promotion==\n{{main|Dark Passion Play World Tour}}\n[[File:Nightwish-Melbourne-2008.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Nightwish ending a concert in [[Melbourne]], on 31 January 2008.]]\nTo promote the release of the album, Nightwish played the ''[[Dark Passion Play World Tour]]'', that took place from 2007 to 2009.\n\nOn 22 September 2007, the band hosted a secret concert at Rock Caf\u00e9 in [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]], disguising itself as a Nightwish [[cover band]] called \"Nachtwasser\".<ref>{{cite news|work=Blabbermouth.net |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=81338 |title=Nightwish performs secret gig in Estonia |date=23 September 2007 |accessdate=7 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011071711/http://roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=81338 |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref> Their first official concert with the new singer was in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]] on 6 October 2007.<ref>{{cite news|work=Blabbermouth.net |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=82280 |title=Nightwish performs first official concert with new singer |date=7 October 2007 |accessdate=7 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011004826/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=82280 |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref> The ''Dark Passion Play'' tour thus started, visiting the United States, Canada, most of Europe, Asia, and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nightwish.com/en/band/tour |title=Nightwish&nbsp;\u2013 Tour Info |publisher=Nightwish.com |accessdate=7 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011191412/http://www.nightwish.com/en/band/tour |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Blabbermouth.net |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=82169 |title=Nightwish Australian tour dates announced |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=7 October 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011084519/http://roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=82169 |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref> In 2008, the band played over 100 shows, with dates in Oceania, Europe and Asia. In November, the band played in South America, and before this leg they took a three-month break; Nightwish began the third leg in 2009, with dates in North America and Europe, and also playing in several summer metal festivals, including [[Graspop Metal Meeting]] and [[Masters of Rock (festival)|Masters of Rock]]. The last show was played in [[Helsinki]], Finland, in front of 10,000 fans.<ref name=\"nw bio\" />\n\nThe support bands were changing throughout the tour. The frequent acts were the Finnish [[pop rock]] female group [[Indica (Finnish band)|Indica]], Swedish metal band [[Sonic Syndicate]] and the Swedish [[industrial metal]] band [[Pain (musical project)|Pain]]. The USA tour was supported by [[Gothic metal]] band [[Paradise Lost (band)|Paradise Lost]].<ref>[http://www.nightwish.com/en/news/archive?month=03&year=2007 \"Nightwish.com \u2013 PARADISE LOST to support NW on the 2007 US tour\"]</ref> In the last concert, the opening band was the Finnish act [[Apocalyptica]]. On 11 March 2009, was released an [[Extended play|EP]]/DVD, ''[[Made in Hong Kong (And in Various Other Places)|Made in Hong Kong]]'', with 8 live tracks recorded during the tour in various concerts; the DVD contains three music videos as well as a documentary featuring material from Israel to South America, directed by Ville Lipi\u00e4inen.<ref name=\"nw bio\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{main|List of Dark Passion Play editions}}\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics  = [[Tuomas Holopainen]]\n| all_music   = Holopainen except where noted\n| headline = Standard Edition\n| title1          = The Poet and the Pendulum\"\n*<small>I. \"White Lands of Empathica\"</small>\n*<small>II. \"Home\"</small>\n*<small>III. \"The Pacific\"</small>\n*<small>IV. \"Dark Passion Play\"</small>\n*<small>V. \"Mother and Father</small>\n| length1         = 13:54\n| title2          = [[Bye Bye Beautiful]]\n| length2         = 4:14\n| title3          = [[Amaranth (song)|Amaranth]]\n| length3         = 3:52\n| title4          = Cadence of Her Last Breath\n| length4         = 4:14\n| title5          = Master Passion Greed\n| length5         = 6:02\n| title6          = [[Eva (Nightwish song)|Eva]]\n| length6         = 4:24\n| title7          = Sahara\n| length7         = 5:48\n| title8          = Whoever Brings the Night\n| note8           = music: [[Emppu Vuorinen]]\n| length8         = 4:17\n| title9          = For the Heart I Once Had\n| length9         = 3:55\n| title10         = [[The Islander (song)|The Islander]]\n| note10          = music: [[Marco Hietala]]\n| length10        = 5:05\n| title11         = Last of the Wilds\n| note11          = instrumental\n| length11        = 5:40\n| title12         = 7 Days to the Wolves\n| note12          = music: Holopainen, Hietala\n| length12        = 7:03\n| title13         = Meadows of Heaven\n| length13        = 7:10\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Bonus track\n| title14         = Escapist\n| length14        = 4:59\n}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2007)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Australia|42|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|5|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Flanders|18|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Wallonia|17|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardCanada|24|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|[[HDU (Croatian Phonographic Association)|Croatian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"cro charts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrt.hr/hr/top20/o_emisiji.html|title=Croatian Top 20|accessdate=1 June 2010|publisher=Roadrunner Records|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623130544/http://www.hrt.hr/hr/top20/o_emisiji.html|archivedate=23 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|[[Czech Republic|Czech Albums Chart]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mam.ihned.cz/c1-22380730-oficialni-ceska-hitparada-ifpi-cr-45-tyden-2007 |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801014529/http://mam.ihned.cz/c1-22380730-oficialni-ceska-hitparada-ifpi-cr-45-tyden-2007 |archive-date=1 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{albumchart|Denmark|18|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Netherlands|5|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|[[European Top 100 Albums]]<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=nightwish|chart=all}}|work=|publisher=Billboard & Rovi Corporation|accessdate=17 January 2011|title=Dark Passion Play- Nightwish}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n{{albumchart|Finland|1|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|France|6|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Germany|1|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Greece|5|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|[[Mahasz|Hungarian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"hun charts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mahasz.hu/?menu=slagerlistak&menu2=archivum|title=Archive: Nightwish|accessdate=1 June 2010|work=|publisher=Magyar Hanglemezkiad\u00f3k Sz\u00f6vets\u00e9ge}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{albumchart|Ireland|62|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Italy|14|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|Japanese Albums Chart ([[Oricon]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/118208/products/724950/1/|title=Dark Passion Play \u2013 Nightwish|accessdate=16 May 2015|publisher=oricon ME inc.|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|54\n|-\n{{albumchart|Mexico|22|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Norway|7|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|[[OLiS|Polish Albums Chart]]<ref>http://olis.onyx.pl/listy/index.asp?idlisty=419&lang=</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n{{albumchart|Spain|33|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Sweden|4|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Switzerland|1|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|25|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|84|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardHardRock|7|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRock|23|album=Dark Passion Play|artist=Nightwish}}\n|-\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2007)\n!align=\"center\"|Position\n|-\n|Austrian Top 75 Albums<ref>{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/2007_album.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323070749/http://austriancharts.at/2007_album.asp |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|69\n|-\n|Finnish Albums Chart{{r|FIN all sales 2007}}\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|French Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Ventes_Album07.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web