{"title_page": "Deering Banjo Company", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox Company\n|company_name=Deering Banjo Company\n|company_logo=Deering-Eagle_stringed-inst_logo_100.jpg\n|logo_size=100px\n|company_slogan=\n|vector_logo=\n|company_type=Private\n|genre=\n|foundation=1975\n|founder=Greg Deering\n|location= [[Spring Valley, San Diego County, California|Spring Valley, California]], [[United States|USA]]\n|origins=\n|key_people=Greg Deering, Janet Deering\n|area_served=Global\n|industry=[[Musical instruments]]\n|products=\n|revenue=\n|operating_income=\n|net_income=\n|num_employees=\n|parent=\n|subsid=[[Vega Company|Vega]], Tenbrooks, Goodtime\n|owner=Greg and Janet Deering\n|homepage=[http://www.deeringbanjos.com/ DeeringBanjos.com] \n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Deering Banjo Company''' was started in 1975 by Greg and Janet Deering.  They are located in [[Spring Valley, San Diego County, California|Spring Valley, California]].  Deering Banjos makes Deering, [[Vega Company|Vega]], Tenbrooks, and Goodtime [[banjo]]s.\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.deeringbanjos.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Banjo manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument manufacturing companies of the United States]]\n\n\n{{musical-instrument-company-stub}}\ndeering banjo company is the creator of many US made banjo such as the goodtime, eagle, and vega series banjo. Made in the US!\nThey donate to the Republican party. Also, proud sponsor of The Donald Trump.\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2008}}\n{{Infobox Company\n|company_name=Deering Banjo Company\n|company_logo=Deering-Eagle_stringed-inst_logo_100.jpg\n|logo_size=100px\n|company_slogan=\n|vector_logo=\n|company_type=Private\n|genre=\n|foundation=1975\n|founder=Greg Deering\n|location= [[Spring Valley, San Diego County, California|Spring Valley, California]], [[United States|USA]]\n|origins=\n|key_people=Greg Deering, Janet Deering\n|area_served=Global\n|industry=[[Musical instruments]]\n|products=\n|revenue=\n|operating_income=\n|net_income=\n|num_employees=\n|parent=\n|subsid=[[Vega Company|Vega]], Tenbrooks, Goodtime\n|owner=Greg and Janet Deering\n|homepage=[http://www.deeringbanjos.com/ DeeringBanjos.com] \n|footnotes= \n}}\n\nThe '''Deering Banjo Company''' was started in 1975 by Greg and Janet Deering.  They are located in [[Spring Valley, San Diego County, California|Spring Valley, California]].  Deering Banjos makes Deering, [[Vega Company|Vega]], Tenbrooks, and Goodtime [[banjo]]s.\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.deeringbanjos.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:Banjo manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument manufacturing companies of the United States]]\n\n\n{{musical-instrument-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:9820:2b30:546f:62ea:18bc:3d31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deering_Banjo_Company"}
{"title_page": "Bison Licking Insect Bite", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[File:F07 0054.Ma.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Bison carved on reindeer [[antler]] fragment, {{ill|National Museum of Prehistory (France)|fr|Mus\u00e9e national de Pr\u00e9histoire|lt=National Museum of Prehistory}} in [[Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil]]]]\n'''''Bison Licking Insect Bite''''' is a [[prehistoric art|prehistoric carving]] from the [[Upper Paleolithic]], found at [[Abri de la Madeleine]] near [[Tursac]] in [[Dordogne]], France, the [[type-site]] of the [[Magdalenian]] culture, which produced many fine small carvings in antler or bone.\n\nCreated sometime between 20,000 and 12,000 [[Before present|BP]] (15,000 BP according to the museum), it was formerly in the [[National Archaeological Museum (France)|Musee des Antiquites Nationales]], [[St. Germain-en-Laye]], but has been transferred to the expanded National Museum of Prehistory in [[Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil]] that opened in 2004, not far from its findspot. It is a carved and engraved fragment of a [[spear-thrower]] made of [[reindeer]] antler. It depicts the figure of a [[bison]], of the now extinct species [[steppe wisent]] (''Bison priscus'') with its head turned around and showing its tongue extended. It is thought the spear-thrower was broken into roughly its present shape before the carving was made from the fragment, hence the need to show the turned-back head of the animal in order to fit the existing structure.<ref>[http://musee-prehistoire-eyzies.fr/en/collection/tid-4/cid-5/collection-bison-se-lechant, \"Collections\", National Museum of Prehistory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430045958/http://musee-prehistoire-eyzies.fr/en/collection/tid-4/cid-5/collection-bison-se-lechant%2C |date=2015-04-30 }} in Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil (in French)</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Stone Age art]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.onlineartcenter.com/prehistoric.html ''Bison Licking Insect Bite'']\n\n{{Prehistoric technology| state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric art]]\n[[Category:Art of the Upper Paleolithic]]\n[[Category:Bison in art]]\n\n\n{{archaeology-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n[[File:F07 0054.Ma.JPG|thumb|300px|right|Bison carved on reindeer [[antler]] fragment, {{ill|National Museum of Prehistory (France)|fr|Mus\u00e9e national de Pr\u00e9histoire|lt=National Museum of Prehistory}} in [[Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil]]]]\n'''''Bison Licking Insect Bite''''' is a [[prehistoric art|prehistoric carving]] from the [[Upper Paleolithic]], found at [[Abri de la Madeleine]] near [[Tursac]] in [[Dordogne]], France, the [[type-site]] of the [[Magdalenian]] culture, which produced many fine small carvings in antler or bone.\n\nCreated sometime between 20,000 and 12,000 [[Before present|BP]] (15,000 BP according to the museum), it was formerly in the [[National Archaeological Museum (France)|Musee des Antiquites Nationales]], [[St. Germain-en-Laye]], but has been transferred to the expanded National Museum of Prehistory in [[Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil]] that opened in 2004, not far from its findspot. It is a carved and engraved fragment of a [[spear-thrower]] made of [[reindeer]] antler. It depicts the figure of a [[bison]], of the now extinct species [[steppe wisent]] (''bison priscus'') with its head turned around and showing its tongue extended. It is thought the spear-thrower was broken into roughly its present shape before the carving was made from the fragment, hence the need to show the turned-back head of the animal in order to fit the existing structure.<ref>[http://musee-prehistoire-eyzies.fr/en/collection/tid-4/cid-5/collection-bison-se-lechant, \"Collections\", National Museum of Prehistory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430045958/http://musee-prehistoire-eyzies.fr/en/collection/tid-4/cid-5/collection-bison-se-lechant%2C |date=2015-04-30 }} in Les Eyzies-de-Tayac-Sireuil (in French)</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Stone Age art]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.onlineartcenter.com/prehistoric.html ''Bison Licking Insect Bite'']\n\n{{Prehistoric technology| state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Prehistoric art]]\n[[Category:Art of the Upper Paleolithic]]\n[[Category:Bison in art]]\n\n\n{{archaeology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Toter Alter Mann", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bison_Licking_Insect_Bite"}
{"title_page": "Karnataka", "text_new": "{{Short description|State in southern India}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Overlinked|date=February 2020}}\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Karnataka\n| official_name                   = \n| type                            = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| image_skyline                   = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a      = Mysore Palace Morning.jpg\n| photo2a      = 7th - 9th century Hindu and Jain temples, Pattadakal monuments Karnataka 5.jpg\n| photo2b      = Shravanabelagola Bahubali wideframe.jpg\n| photo3a      = Hoysala emblem.jpg\n| photo3b      = DGTF2318.jpg\n| photo4a      = Gol Gumbaz from gardens.jpg\n| photo4b      = Yakshagana new.jpg\n| photo5a      = Hampi virupaksha temple.jpg\n| spacing                   = 1\n| color_border              = white\n| color                     = black\n| size                      = 280\n| foot_montage = ''From top, left to right:''<br />[[Mysore Palace]], [[Pattadakal]], [[Gommateshwara statue]] , [[Hoysala Empire]] emblem, [[Shivanasamudra Falls]], [[Gol Gumbaz]], [[Yakshagana]] Dance and [[Virupaksha Temple, Hampi]]\n}}\n| image_blank_emblem              = Karnataka emblem.svg\n| blank_emblem_type               = [[Emblem of Karnataka|Emblem]]\n| blank_emblem_size               = 100px\n| anthem                          = \"[[Jaya Bharata Jananiya Tanujate]]\"{{ref|est|}}\n<br />\"(Victory To You Mother Karnataka, Daughter of Mother India)\"\n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location of Karnataka in [[India]]\n| image_map1                      = IN-KA.svg\n| map_caption1                    = Map of Karnataka\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|12.97|77.50|region:IN-KA_type:adm1st_dim:500000|display=inline,t