{"title_page": "Delaware House of Representatives", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox legislature\n| background_color = {{Democratic Party (US)/meta/color}}\n| name              = Delaware House of Representatives\n| legislature       = [[Delaware General Assembly]]\n| coa_pic           = Seal_of_Delaware.svg\n| session_room      =DE State House.jpg \n| house_type        = Lower house\n| term_limits       = None\n| new_session       = January 9, 2018\n| leader1_type      = [[Speaker of the Delaware House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]]\n| leader1           = [[Peter Schwartzkopf]]\n| party1            = ([[Delaware Democratic Party|D]])\n| election1         = January 8, 2013\n| leader2_type      = Majority Leader\n| leader2           = [[Valerie Longhurst]]\n| party2            = ([[Delaware Democratic Party|D]])\n| election2         = January 8, 2013\n| leader4_type      = Minority Leader\n| leader4           = [[Daniel Short]]\n| party4            = ([[Delaware Republican Party|R]])\n| election4         = January 8, 2013\n| term_length       = 2 years\n| authority         = Article III, Section 1, [[Delaware Constitution]]\n| salary            = $45,291/year<ref>https://budget.delaware.gov/budget/fy2018/documents/hb275-hs1.pdf</ref>\n| members           = 41\n|structure1        = House_of_Representatives_diagram_2014_State_of_Deleware.svg\n| structure1_res = 250px\n| political_groups1 =\n'''Majority'''\n*{{nowrap|{{Color box|#0000FF|border=darkgray}} [[Delaware Democratic Party|Democratic]] (26)}}\n'''Minority'''\n*{{nowrap|{{Color box|#FF0000|border=darkgray}} [[Delaware Republican Party|Republican]] (15)}}\n | last_election1    = [[Delaware House of Representatives election, 2018|November 6, 2018]]<br>(41 seats)\n | next_election1    = November 3, 2020<br>(41 seats)\n| redistricting     = Legislative Control\n| meeting_place     = House of Representatives Chamber<br>[[Delaware Legislative Hall]]<br>[[Dover, Delaware|Dover]], Delaware\n| website           = [http://legis.delaware.gov/ legis.delaware.gov]\n}}\n\nThe '''Delaware House of Representatives''' is the [[lower house]] of the [[Delaware General Assembly]], the [[State legislature (United States)|state legislature]] of the US state of [[Delaware]]. It is composed of 1 Representative from an equal number of constituencies, each of whom is elected to a two-year term. Its members are not subject to [[term limits]]. The House meets at the [[Delaware State Capitol|Delaware Legislative Hall]] in [[Dover, Delaware|Dover]].\n\n==Name==\nFrom 1776 to 1792, the chamber was known as the [[House of Assembly]], a common name for [[lower house]]s of colonial legislatures and states under the [[Articles of Confederation|Confederation]]. The name was changed by Delaware's [[Delaware Constitution of 1792|1792 Constitution]], reflecting the new federal [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]]. This change on the part of Delaware initiated a movement that has resulted in a majority of the lower houses of [[State legislature (United States)|U.S. state legislatures]] sharing the name of the federal House of Representatives.\n\n==Leadership==\nThe [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker of the House]] presides over the House of Representatives. The Speaker is elected by the majority party caucus followed by confirmation of the full House through the passage of a House Resolution. The Speaker is the chief leadership position of the body. The other House leaders are elected by their respective party caucuses. The Majority Leader determines which bills are brought to the floor for debate from an Agenda prepared by the Speaker of the House and manages debates and floor votes.\n\n[[Terry Spence]] (R) was the longest serving speaker in the history of the Delaware General Assembly.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Office !! Representative !! Party !! District\n|-\n| [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker of the House]]\n| [[Peter Schwartzkopf]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democratic\n| 14\n|-\n| Majority Leader\n| [[Valerie Longhurst]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democratic\n| 15\n|-\n| Majority Whip\n| [[John Mitchell Jr. (politician)|John Mitchell, Jr.]]\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democratic\n| 13\n|-\n| Minority Leader\n| [[Daniel Short]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 39\n|-\n| Minority Whip\n| [[Timothy Dukes]]\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| 40\n|}\n\n==Qualifications==\nMembers of the House of Representatives must be citizens of the United States, have lived in Delaware for three years, been a resident of their constituent district for at least one year preceding their election, and must be at least 24 years old by the time of their election.\n\n==Current composition==\n{| style=\"width:50%\"\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#33F; width:63.0%; text-align:center; color:white\" | '''26'''\n<!--| style= \"background:#FFFFFF; width:0.0%; text-align:center; color:black\"|-->\n| style=\"background:#F33; width:37.0%; text-align:center; color:white\" | '''15'''\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#33F\" | '''Democratic'''\n<!--|--> \n| style=\"text-align:center; color:#F33\" | '''Republican'''\n|}\n\n{|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; width:40%\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:bottom;\"\n!rowspan=3|Affiliation\n!colspan=2|Party<br />{{small|(Shading indicates majority caucus)}}\n!rowspan=3|Total\n!\n|-style=\"height:5px\"\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" |\n| style=\"background-color:{{Republican Party (United States)/meta/color}}\" |\n| style=\"background-color:black\" |\n|-\n![[Delaware Democratic Party|Democratic]]\n![[Delaware Republican Party|Republican]]\n!Vacant\n|-\n!nowrap style=\"font-size:80%\"|November 7, 2018<ref>Delaware legislators' terms begin the second Wednesday in November (i.e. the day after [[Election Day (United States)|Election Day]]), even though they are not sworn in until January. [http://delcode.delaware.gov/constitution/constitution-19.shtml#P1045_165217 Constitution of Delaware, Article II, Section 3]</ref>\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|26\n| 15\n! 41\n| 0\n|-\n!Latest voting share\n!{{party shading/Democratic}}|{{percentage|26|41|1}}\n!{{percentage|15|41|1}}\n!{{percentage|41|41|0}}\n!{{percentage|0|41|0}}\n|}\n\n===Current members, 2018\u20132020===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! District !! Name !! Party !! First Elected !! Residence\n|-\n| 1 || [[Nnamdi Chukwuocha]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2018 || [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]]\n|-\n| 2 || [[Stephanie Bolden]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2010 || Wilmington\n|-\n| 3 || [[Sherry Dorsey Walker]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2018 || Wilmington \n|-\n| 4 || [[Gerald Brady]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2006 || [[Wilmington, Delaware|West Wilmington]]\n|-\n| 5 || [[Kendra Johnson]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2018 || [[New Castle, Delaware|New Castle]]\n|-\n| 6 || [[Debra Heffernan]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2010 || [[Edgewood Hills, Delaware|Edgewood Hills]]\n|-\n| 7 || [[Ray Seigfried]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2018 ||\n|-\n| 8 || [[S. Quinton Johnson]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2008 || [[Middletown, Delaware|Middletown]]\n|-\n| 9 || [[Kevin Hensley (politician)|Kevin Hensley]] || {{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep || 2014 || \n|-\n| 10 || [[Sean Matthews]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2014 || \n|-\n| 11 || [[Jeffrey Spiegelman]] || {{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep || 2012 || [[Clayton, Delaware|Clayton]]\n|-\n| 12 || [[Krista Griffith]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2018 || [[Fairfax, Delaware|Fairfax]]\n|-\n| 13 || [[John Mitchell Jr. (politician)|John Mitchell Jr.]] || {{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem || 2006 || [[Elsmere, Delaware|Elsmere]]\n|-\n| 14 || [[Peter Schwartzkopf]] || {{